## Introduction to Clock Design

Building a Real-Time Clock (RTC) is a fundamental exercise in digital electronics. It requires a solid understanding of frequency dividers and structural architecture.

### The Core Components

To build a stable RTC on an FPGA, you need several distinct modules working in perfect synchronization:

1. A **1 Hz tick generator** (derived from the board's base clock).
1. Cascaded counters for seconds, minutes, and hours.
1. A multiplexer for the display driver.

## VHDL Architecture

Let's look at how we can implement the basic seconds counter. This requires understanding synchronous logic and strict state transitions.

### The Modulo-60 Counter

Here is a standard implementation of a seconds counter in VHDL. Notice how the synchronous reset is handled inside the main clocked process to prevent race conditions.

```
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;

entity sec_counter is
    Port ( clk : in STD_LOGIC;
           reset : in STD_LOGIC;
           tick_1hz : in STD_LOGIC;
           sec_out : out integer range 0 to 59);
end sec_counter;

architecture Behavioral of sec_counter is
    signal count : integer range 0 to 59 := 0;
begin
    process(clk)
    begin
        if rising_edge(clk) then
            if reset = '1' then
                count <= 0;
            elsif tick_1hz = '1' then
                if count = 59 then
                    count <= 0;
                else
                    count <= count + 1;
                end if;
            end if;
        end if;
    end process;

    sec_out <= count;
end Behavioral;
Conclusion
Once the seconds are perfectly synchronized, cascading the minutes and hours is a simple extension of the same logic. Next, we will translate these integers into BCD.
